    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-02-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-02-01T18:00:00-05:00" n="326"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d326">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AA/2–151: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Netherlands</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d326fn1">Repeated to Canberra as telegram 204, to Brussels
                        as telegram 1054 for action, and to the U.S. Mission in New York as telegram
                        678 for information.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-02-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 1, 1951—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>908. Dept believes <gloss target="#t_UNCI1">UNCI</gloss>’s usefulness <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> diminishing and continuation of Comm in
                    inactive status detrimental to its prestige, that of <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> and potential source of irritation to <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss>s.</p>
                <p>Since ex-<gloss target="#t_KNIL1">KNIL</gloss> problem may be liquidated next
                    month, we believe target date of Mar 31 for dissolution Comm reasonable.
                    Argument may be put forward that one of Neth’s proposals for solution <gloss
                        target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss> problem included mediation by <gloss
                        target="#t_UNCI1">UNCI</gloss> and that therefore Comm shld not be dissolved
                    while there exists possibility it might be useful in solution <gloss
                        target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss>. Dept convinced, however, <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s will not accept intervention in substance
                        <gloss target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss> by Comm as presently constituted. If
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> mediation this problem desirable, there no
                    reason why other <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> machinery for mediation, such
                    as conciliation panel, might not be used. View fact that neither party has
                    utilized services of Comm for many months now we do not believe that maintaining
                        <gloss target="#t_UNCI1">UNCI</gloss> solely for possible use in <gloss
                        target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss> problem either necessary or desirable. Light
                    foregoing, suggest you approach <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> in
                    attempt secure agreement on target date Mar 31 for dissolution Comm assuring
                    them such dissolution unrelated our minds matter keeping <gloss target="#t_NNG1"
                        >NNG</gloss> negots fluid and flexible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
